    width: 90vw;
    max-width: 300px;
  }
}

@media only screen and (max-width: 320px) {
  .container {
    height: auto;
  }

  .item {
    width: 90vw;
    max-width: 200px;
  }
}
```

### 5. Use `min-height` and `min-width` for Minimum Constraints

Sometimes, setting minimum constraints can help prevent layout shifts.

```css
.container {
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: column;
  align-items: center;
  justify-content: center;
  padding: 10px;
  min-height: 300px; /* Ensure a minimum height */
}

.item {
  flex: 1;
  margin: 10px;
  box-sizing: border-box;
  min-width: 200px; /* Ensure a minimum width */
  width: 90vw;
  max-width: 300px;
}
```

### 6. Avoid `position: absolute` and `position: fixed` Unless Necessary

While `position: absolute` and `position: fixed` can be useful in certain scenarios, they can also cause layout shifts if not used carefully. Use them sparingly and only when necessary.

### 7. Use `object-fit` for Images

If you are dealing with images, ensure they are scaled properly to avoid layout shifts.

```css
.image-container img {
  width: 100%;
  height: auto;
  object-fit: cover; /* Ensures the image covers the container without distortion */
}
```

### Conclusion

By using flexible units, avoiding fixed dimensions, and ensuring your media queries are set up correctly, you can minimize layout shifts and improve the user experience on mobile devices. If you continue to experience issues, consider using browser developer tools to inspect and adjust your layout dynamically.

